To add a value to an array in a behavior subject you don&#39;t mutate the contents of the array, you create a new array and then get the behavior subject to emit that new array.

    this.users.next([..this.users.value, user]);

To create a new observable from a value just use of

    of(user);

Why is your api returning a promise? The http service returns observables so you should be able to just return the http mapped to a user object.

    

    return this.api.get(&#39;users/&#39; + id, this.userService.getAuthToken(), ).pipe(
      map(functionToMapResponseToAUserObject),
      tap(sideEfectFunctionToInsertNewUserIntoBehaviorSubject)
    )

So your service could be if you modify your api to return an observable instead of a promise

    getUserInfo(id: string): Observable&lt;User&gt; {
      const users = this.users.getValue();
      const user = users.find((u) =&gt; u._id === id);
      return user
        ? of(user)
        : this.api.get(&#39;users/&#39; + id, this.userService.getAuthToken(), ).pipe(
          map(response =&gt; new User(response)),
          tap(user =&gt; { this.users.next([...users, user]); })
        )
    }

If you cannot modify the api the use from to convert the promise to an observable

    from(this.api.get(&#39;users/&#39; + id, this.userService.getAuthToken(), ))

To stop multiple requests to the same id you would need an object that keeps track of which ones are loading

    loading: { [key]: Observable&lt;User&gt; } = {};

Add a share replay to the api call so the api call will not be repeated and stick it in the loading cache

     let loaded = false;
     const user$ = this.api.get(&#39;users/&#39; + id, this.userService.getAuthToken(), ).pipe(
        map(response =&gt; new User(response)),
        tap(user =&gt; {
          this.users.next([...users, user]);
          if (loading[id]) {
            delete loading[id];
          }
          loaded = true;
        }),
        shareReplay()
     );

     if (!loaded) {
       loading[id] = user$;
     }

Then you could see if one is loading before firing off an api call and return the observable from the loading cache.

Adrian&#39;s answer is close, but does not quite answer one part of your question:

&gt; So when I call getUser 2 times simultaneously with the same id it should request just once.

Adrian&#39;s solution does not do this, since if the request did not resolve yet the user will not be stored yet and you&#39;ll end up requesting the user twice.

Instead the general recommended approach is to store your cache as a map of observables.

Pseudo typescript, syntax might be wrong, I&#39;ll also make the assumption that you can turn the api call into an observable, look for Adrian&#39;s answer on how to deal with it if not: 
```typescript
users: Map&lt;string,Observable&lt;User&gt;&gt; = new Map();


getUserInfo(id: string): Observable&lt;User&gt; {
  if(!this.users.get(id)){
     const userObservable = this.api.get(&#39;users/&#39; + id, this.userService.getAuthToken(), ) // Or turn the promise to observable with `from`
       .pipe(
         map(response =&gt; new User(response)),
         share(),
       );
     this.users.set(id, userObservable) 
  }

  return this.users.get(id)

}
```

Please try this approach, I believe it will satisfy your needs

    usersSubject = new Subject&lt;User&gt;();
    usersCache = this.usersSubject.pipe(
      scan&lt;Record&lt;string, User&gt;&gt;((cache, user) =&gt; {
        cache[user.id] = user;
        return cache;
      }, {}),
      shareReplay(1) // keeping the last version of the cache
    );


    getUserInfo(id: string): Observable&lt;User&gt; {
      return this.usersCache.pipe(
        pluck(id),
        switchMap(user =&gt; iif(() =&gt; !user,
          this.api.get(&#39;users/&#39; + id, this.userService.getAuthToken()).pipe(
            tap(user =&gt; this.usersSubject.next(user)) // caching the user
          ),
          of(user)
        ),
        first() // auto unsubscription, because usersCache will keep pushing values
      )
    }

UPDATE:
Make sure to maintain a subscription open to keep the cache intact (I guess it is a service, so do it in constructor): 

    this.usersCache.subscribe()

